  "unmapped_findings": [
    "Fracture surface evolution: Zr0 shows small dimples and cleavage faces, while Zr0.01 and Zr0.50 exhibit larger, deeper dimples and increased dimple density, indicating improved ductility.",
    "Formation mechanism of bimodal grain structure in Zr0.50 steel: The combined effects of Zr solute drag and Zener pinning by nanoscale ZrC particles retard recrystallization, leading to partial recrystallization and bimodal grain structure. Micro shear bands from cold-rolling provide nucleation sites for fine grains.",
    "According to thermodynamic calculation (Thermo-Calc, Fig. 7), the equilibrium fraction of ZrC in Zr0.50 steel at 900°C is ~0.6%.",
    "HDI strengthening contribution in Zr0.50 is estimated to be ~300 MPa (based on Hall-Petch and back-stress models). Precipitation strengthening from ZrC is calculated as ~108 MPa.",
    "Critical twinning stress for the FCC matrix in Zr0.50 is calculated to be ~1.14 GPa (using SFE of ~55 mJ/m^2), which is lower than the true ultimate tensile strength, enabling deformation twinning.",
    "Deformation mechanisms in Zr0.50 involve dislocation slip, slip bands, nanotwinning, and HDI hardening; the synergistic effect of HDI hardening and twinning enhances strain hardening and ductility.",
    "The quasi-in-situ EBSD+μ-DIC analysis (Fig. 5) confirms strain partitioning between soft CG and hard FG zones, with GNDs accumulating at hetero-interfaces, contributing to HDI strengthening."
  ]
}